docs {
  # atomic-fi-scenarios

  The canonical Bruno collection for the **AtomicFi payments compliance platform**.
  Every regulatory scenario from the use-case catalog at
  [`guides/use-cases.md`](https://github.com/alvera-ai/atomic-fi/blob/main/guides/use-cases.md)
  is exercised here against the live HTTP API, so the same artefact serves three purposes:

  - **Demo tape** — Bruno's recursive runner walks the entire collection in one click,
    producing realistic data and a green status board suitable for a live customer demo.
  - **Regression smoke** — `bru run --env local` from CI catches contract drift between
    the OpenAPI spec, the Phoenix controllers, and the documented scenarios.
  - **Compliance evidence** — each scenario maps to a row in the catalog, so a regulator
    or auditor can request "scenario §2.3.1 (OFAC SDN exact match)" and receive exactly
    one piece of executable evidence with one assertion path.

  ## Scenario catalog

  Eleven folders live in this collection: one baseline smoke plus ten regulatory
  scenarios. Each scenario folder is a self-contained, regulator-walkable narrative
  with its own `001-auth.bru` + `002-warmup.bru` prelude, so it can be run in
  isolation (`bru run <folder> --env local`) and re-run idempotently without
  leaning on any other folder's state.

  | Folder | Catalog # | Regulation cited | Lifecycle | Count |
  | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
  | `smoke-tests/` | — | baseline data seed | all pass | 29 |
  | `de-minimis-ach/` | #1 | 31 CFR §1020.220 (CIP minimum thresholds) | PASS | 7 |
  | `cip-kyc-in-progress/` | #6 | BSA §326 / 31 CFR §1020.220 (CIP identity verification) | BLOCK → PUT `kyc_status:approved` → PASS | 9 |
  | `prohibited-risk-freeze/` | #10 | 31 CFR §1010.230 (CDD) + internal/lawful-order freeze | BLOCK (`risk_level: prohibited`) | 7 |
  | `ofac-sdn-high-score/` | #11 | 31 CFR §501.404 (OFAC SDN screening) | BLOCK → mark false-positive → PASS | 11 |
  | `ah-country-kp-residence/` | #15 | OFAC E.O. 13466 (comprehensive DPRK sanctions) | BLOCK → PUT residence → PASS | 9 |
  | `ctr-sub-threshold-structuring/` | #19 | 31 USC §5324 + 31 CFR §1020.320 (CTR/structuring) | PASS × 2 → BLOCK on velocity | 9 |
  | `smurfing-pattern-sar-eligible/` | #20 | 31 USC §5324 + 31 CFR §1020.320 (smurfing typology) | PASS × 5 → BLOCK (SAR eligible) | 22 |
  | `business-ah-zero-bos/` | #27 | Corporate Transparency Act / 31 CFR §1010.380 (FinCEN CDD UBO) | BLOCK → POST beneficial owner → PASS | 9 |
  | `ofac-mixer-usdc/` | #34 | 31 CFR §501.404 + GENIUS Act §4(a)(5) (mixer wallet) | BLOCK on recipient wallet | 7 |
  | `internal-blocklist-lastname/` | #41 | FFIEC BSA/AML Manual (internal-list screening) | seed entry → refresh cache → BLOCK | 10 |

  ## Scenario detail

  ### `smoke-tests/` — baseline data seed (29 requests)
  Not a regulatory scenario; the green smoke that proves the harness is healthy
  before any compliance assertions run. Auth → BlocklistCache warmup → 2 AccountHolders
  (nested LegalEntity, KYC-approved, low-risk, US individual) → 5 Counterparties
  (~75% individual / 25% business, mostly US with occasional GB / DE / FR / BR / MX) →
  20 Transactions (random AH × random CP, $5–$5000). `chain_screening: false`
  throughout so the smoke runs even when Watchman is down. Idempotent on
  `external_entry_id`. End state: 2 AHs, 5 CPs, 20 TXs in the local DB.

  ### `de-minimis-ach/` — scenario #1, de minimis ACH (PASS)
  31 CFR §1020.220 — CIP minimum-information thresholds. The verified happy-path:
  fully-onboarded individual (KYC approved, low risk) sends a small ACH to a clean
  recipient. No rule should trip. This is the regression anchor — if `de-minimis-ach`
  ever flips to BLOCK, something in the rule engine has drifted.

  ### `cip-kyc-in-progress/` — scenario #6, CIP KYC gate (BLOCK → PASS)
  BSA §326 (31 CFR §1020.220) — banks must verify customer identity before
  permitting account activity. Onboards the sender with `kyc_status: in_progress`
  (identified but not verified). The transaction trips the `cip_kyc_not_approved`
  rule. PUT the AH to `kyc_status: approved` and the retry passes — regulator-walkable
  evidence of the gate opening only after the BSA §326 check completes.

  ### `prohibited-risk-freeze/` — scenario #10, prohibited risk freeze (BLOCK)
  31 CFR §1010.230 (CDD) plus lawful-order / internal-compliance context. The AH
  is fully identified but compliance has classified them `risk_level: prohibited` —
  the lever a bank pulls when an account must stay on-platform (audit / investigation)
  but no funds may move. The `prohibited_risk_freeze` rule reads
  `account_holder.risk_level` and emits BLOCK regardless of amount, counterparty,
  or any other signal.

  ### `ofac-sdn-high-score/` — scenario #11, OFAC SDN exact hit (BLOCK → PASS)
  31 CFR §501.404 — every party to a US-jurisdiction transaction must be screened
  against the OFAC SDN list before settlement. The receiver matches the live
  moov/watchman :8084 SDN feed with a high score. The transaction is BLOCKed.
  An ops user marks the screening `false_positive: true` via the compliance API;
  the retry passes. Demonstrates the full SDN review-and-override lifecycle.

  ### `ah-country-kp-residence/` — scenario #15, sanctioned residence (BLOCK → PASS)
  OFAC E.O. 13466 — comprehensive DPRK sanctions; all transactions involving
  KP-resident parties are blocked absent a specific licence. The platform does
  not refuse onboarding (a sanctioned resident may legitimately need a US bank
  account to receive remittances), but every outbound transaction is blocked
  until the residence record changes. The `ah_country_kp_residence` rule walks
  the AH's LegalEntity addresses, finds the primary residential one, and emits
  BLOCK whenever `country ∈ {KP, IR, CU, SY}`. PUT the address to a non-sanctioned
  country and the retry passes.

  ### `ctr-sub-threshold-structuring/` — scenario #19, structuring (PASS×2 → BLOCK)
  31 USC §5324 (anti-structuring statute) + 31 CFR §1020.320 (CTR $10,000
  threshold). The structuring rule does NOT look at risk class — anyone can
  structure; the signal is the velocity pattern across recent debits. Three
  rapid-fire debits each just under the CTR threshold; the third trips the
  `ctr_sub_threshold_structuring` rule and is held SAR-eligible.

  ### `smurfing-pattern-sar-eligible/` — scenario #20, smurfing (PASS×5 → BLOCK)
  31 USC §5324 + 31 CFR §1020.320 — the textbook smurfing typology. One sender,
  many small debits to many distinct recipients inside a 24-hour window — a single
  party fanning out cash through multiple agents to disguise the total. The first
  five debits clear, the sixth trips the smurfing detector. The longest scenario
  in the collection (22 requests) precisely because the typology requires the
  fan-out to be visible in the ledger before it can be detected.

  ### `business-ah-zero-bos/` — scenario #27, business with no UBOs (BLOCK → PASS)
  Corporate Transparency Act + 31 CFR §1010.380 (FinCEN CDD rule). The CTA
  requires US legal entities to report every UBO with ≥25% ownership OR
  substantial control. The business AH onboards fine (the platform doesn't
  refuse to open the account), but no outbound payment can settle until at
  least one BO is on file. POST a beneficial owner (60% shareholder, nested
  LegalEntity) and the retry passes — the gate opens.

  ### `ofac-mixer-usdc/` — scenario #34, mixer wallet (BLOCK)
  31 CFR §501.404 + GENIUS Act §4(a)(5) — stablecoin issuers must screen
  recipient wallets against OFAC's sanctioned addresses (Tornado Cash and
  similar mixers). Block fires on the recipient wallet, not the sender. The
  sender is a clean, fully-onboarded individual; the verdict comes entirely
  from the counterparty side.

  ### `internal-blocklist-lastname/` — scenario #41, tenant blocklist (BLOCK)
  FFIEC BSA/AML Examination Manual — internal-list screening obligations
  beyond OFAC SDN. The compliance ops surface for parties the bank itself has
  reason to watch: typos surfaced in investigations, names from law-enforcement
  letters, internal close-out lists. POST a blocklist entry
  (`scope: last_name`, `term: "Smurf"`) → trigger a synchronous
  `BlocklistCache` refresh (Quantum normally does this hourly) → create the
  receiver → the transaction trips the blocklist rule.

  ## Quick start

  1. **Install Bruno** — `brew install --cask bruno` or download from <https://www.usebruno.com>.
  2. **Bring atomic-fi up locally** from the repo root:
     ```
     make run-backing-services   # docker compose: upstream moov/watchman on :8084
     make server                  # Phoenix on :4100
     ```
  3. **Refresh bootstrap creds** so the local env matches what's in the running DB:
     ```
     mix atomic_fi.dump_bootstrap_creds
     ```
  4. **Copy the env template** (one-time):
     ```
     cp environments/local.example.bru environments/local.bru
     ```
     Then edit `local.bru` with the values from `priv/repo/.bootstrap_creds.json`.
  5. **Run a scenario** — either click the Runner button in the Bruno UI, or from CLI.
     The smoke is the fastest green:
     ```
     cd bruno/atomic-fi-scenarios
     bru run smoke-tests --env local
     ```
     Any scenario folder runs the same way (each ships its own auth + warmup):
     ```
     bru run ofac-sdn-high-score --env local
     bru run cip-kyc-in-progress --env local
     ```
     Recursive Run from the collection root walks every folder in order.

  Expected smoke result: **29/29 requests pass, 66/66 assertions green** in roughly 4 seconds.

  ## Authentication

  All requests after `001-auth.bru` use bearer authentication. `001-auth.bru` exchanges
  `{email, password, tenant_slug}` for a session bearer via `POST /api/sessions`; the
  token, tenant id, and running id arrays (`ahIds`, `cpIds`) are stashed as env vars by
  the post-response script and reused by every downstream request.

  `001-auth.bru` also resets the running id arrays on every invocation, so re-runs start
  from a clean state without manual env clearing.

  ## Design principles

  - **Real Watchman, real BlocklistCache, real DB.** No mocks anywhere — compliance
    scenarios must validate the actual pipeline. The compose-managed
    `moov/watchman:v0.61.1` container is part of the test harness.
  - **One scenario, one `.bru` file.** A regulator can request "scenario 23" and receive
    exactly one piece of executable evidence.
  - **Child entities are nested via `cast_assoc`**, not created via standalone endpoints.
    A counterparty POST carries its LegalEntity inline; the HTTP surface stays smaller
    than the DB schema count.
  - **Idempotency via the external SoE identifier.** Counterparty creation is
    get-or-create on `external_id`; the same POST replayed returns the original
    record unchanged. Updates use PUT.
  - **Per-tenant RLS isolation.** Every assertion runs inside the platform tenant's
    session scope; cross-tenant visibility is explicitly tested via secondary tenants in
    the regulatory folders.

